Not only is it a nice name for it, but it also seems to be the only thing of any value to have come out of the last five years. Of course it would help if that cultural, commercial and economic success story turned out to be sustainable, so that there was something that would last for Cambodians and visitors for more than eighteen months. Reportedly it is not. As Chinese billionaires buy everything from beachfront to gorgeous natural areas, it becomes even more difficult for residents (who ever that may be) to plan for the future. Not all the high-net worth infastructure tycoons in the world are going to be able to save Cambodia a deep economic dive, which is why current residents should be investing in the exact same thing. Oh, and of course, if more real estate is bought up and property ownership become more unobtainable, fewer people are going to be able to afford to stay for any length of time. It is just unsustainable is all. Sound prescient from an unscrupulous Internet nobody, who is probably hiding under his bed somewhere in the depths of Siem Reap?
